            <fr:display-uri>002A</fr:display-uri>
            <fr:route>/002A/</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Writing axiomatic proofs">Writing axiomatic proofs</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The next thing to learn is how to <html:em>write</html:em> an axiomatic proof in any of these systems.
Here's how we'll do it: as a grid with three columns and some number of rows.
Let me give you an example proof in here, and then we'll discuss how it works:
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://www.my-great-forest.net/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://www.my-great-forest.net/0028/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0028</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/0028/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="first example proof">first example proof</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>1</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p) \rightarrow  (q \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  q) \rightarrow  p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>K</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>2</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>K</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>3</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(q \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  q) \rightarrow  p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>MP</html:strong>: 1, 2</html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>4</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(q \rightarrow  q) \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>K</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>5</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>I</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>6</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  q]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>MP</html:strong>: 4, 5</html:td>
</html:tr>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>7</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>MP</html:strong>: 3, 6</html:td>
</html:tr>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>Every line in this proof has three ingredients: a number, a sentence, and a justification.
The numbers are just line numbers.
They count upwards; there's nothing special going on there.</html:p>
            <html:p>The sentences are what we're proving.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://www.my-great-forest.net/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://www.my-great-forest.net/0029/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0029</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/0029/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="proof of, proves">proof of, proves</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>An axiomatic proof is a <html:strong>proof of</html:strong> a sentence iff that sentence occurs on the last line of the proof; saying that the proof <html:strong>proves</html:strong> the sentence means the same thing.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>
So the above proof is a proof of the sentence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex>.
It is a different proof from this next example, which is also a proof of that same sentence: 
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://www.my-great-forest.net/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>16</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://www.my-great-forest.net/002F/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>002F</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/002F/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="tiny example proof">tiny example proof</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:table>

<html:tr>
  <html:td>1</html:td>
  <html:td><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \rightarrow  q \rightarrow  p]]></fr:tex></html:td>
  <html:td><html:strong>K</html:strong></html:td>
</html:tr>
</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>Finally, the justifications are what makes these <html:em>proofs</html:em>, rather than just numbered lists of sentences.
This is the key procedure we follow to construct proofs: every line in a proof has to have a justification, and the justifications restrict what sentences we can prove.
These justifications come in two kinds: one for axioms and one for rules.
When the sentence on a line is an axiom, we can give a justification just by saying what kind of axiom it is.
This is where it is important to remember what proof system we are working in!
The axioms of a proof system are available for use in this way; no other sentences are.
So the above example proof is a proof in <html:strong>SKI</html:strong> and <html:strong>SKIP</html:strong>, but it is not a proof in <html:strong>SK</html:strong>, since line 5 is not an axiom of <html:strong>SK</html:strong>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>When the sentence on a line is not an axiom, it must be justified by some rule.
Here we have only one choice, for all three of our systems: the rule <html:strong>MP</html:strong> of modus ponens.
It's not enough just to list the rule.
<html:strong>MP</html:strong> lets us conclude new sentences <html:em>from sentences we have already proved</html:em>; we have to indicate, then, which already-proved sentences those are.
As you can see, in the first example, line 3 comes by <html:strong>MP</html:strong> from lines 1 and 2; line 6 comes by <html:strong>MP</html:strong> from lines 4 and 5; and line 7 comes by <html:strong>MP</html:strong> from lines 3 and 6.</html:p>
            <html:p>There's an important principle here: any justification in a proof can only refer to lines that occur <html:em>above</html:em> it.
This is obeyed in the above example.
This matters because axiomatic proofs are about building up new proofs using the rule(s) from proofs that we <html:em>already</html:em> have.
</html:p>
            <html:p>The process of <html:em>finding</html:em> a proof is often messy and full of trial and error.
But the proof itself doesn't reflect that messiness; it's a cleaned up string of reasoning that can be read from top to bottom.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
